AGI - "Despite his final fragility and suffering" he gave himself "until the last day of his earthly life" and "in the face of the rage of the many wars" by the "human horrors" "he incessantly elevated his voice by begging for peace" inviting to find possible solutions. Cardinal Giovanni Battista Re, Dean of the College of Cardinals, in his homily, during the funeral Mass of Pope Francis, outlined with emotion the charism and the guiding thread of the mission of the Argentine Pontiff.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
Many applauses that have interrupted the words of King, in front of the powerful of the Earth, which Francis urged several times to seek a dialogue, and that now, on the day of his last greeting to the earthly world, seems, judging by the photos circulating, they have begun to dialogue. Despite the solemnity of the exequial Mass, with its rites and gestures (the funerals were broadcast live in 15 languages, including 4 of the signs), observing the simple wooden casket at the center of the San Pietro square, is strong the awareness of how Bergoglio was really the Pope of all, indeed of "todos, todos, todos", as he often loved to repeat. Cardinal Re remarked how much for Francis the Church had to be "a house for all; a house with always open doors".
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
The cardinal resumed the so dear image of the Pope, "of the Church as a 'field hospital' after a battle in which there were many wounded; a Church eager to take care with determination of the problems of the people and the great sufferings that tear the contemporary world; a Church able to bend over every man, beyond every creed or condition, healing its wounds."
&nbsp;
And then the "numerable gestures" and exhortations for refugees and refugees: as the journey to Lampedusa (the first of Bergoglio made in Italy) and to Lesbos or the moving celebration of the border between Mexico and the United States. In the history will remain the journey in Iraq "complete challenging every risk", observed the cardinal underlining the two key words of Pope Francis: "mercy and joy of the Gospel".
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
His intense pontificate touched "the minds and hearts", he specified the Dean of the College of Cardinals recalling the "great spontaneity" of Francis, his "language rich in images and metaphors". A Pope "in the midst of people with an open heart to all", close to all, "with a strong attention to people in difficulty, spending without measure, especially for the last of the earth, the marginalized", a Pope who did not tire of denouncing the "culture of waste" and to oppose to it a "culture of encounter and solidarity".
&nbsp;
Over 250 thousand people on the festival. Next to the greats of the Earth, the people Francis loved: the last, the forgotten. Like the group composed of poor, migrants, transgenders and detainees, who welcomed the feretro of the Argentine Pope, to Santa Maria Maggiore, after a funeral procession, which has traveled the symbolic places of Rome, between two wings of crowds. On the way to the basilica that guards the icon loved by Francis, the Salus Populi Romani, in thousands have descended into the square (over 150 thousand) to applaud the passage of the papamobile (used on his journey to Mexico in 2016) and readapt. Pope Francis "will conclude his speeches and meetings by saying: "Don't forget to pray for me," the celebrant King concluded.
&nbsp;
"Dear Pope Francis, now we ask you to pray for us and from heaven You bless the Church, bless Rome, bless the whole world. As you did last Sunday from the balcony of this Basilica in a last embrace with all the people of God, but ideally also with humanity seeking truth with sincere heart and keeping high the torch of hope." &nbsp;
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
